> Heads-up: This isn't the mayo-drenched chicken salad that Aunt Sally brings to every family picnic. Picture this: Bok choy and napa cabbage get tossed with chicken in a creamy gochujang dressing that's tangy with a little kick of heat from the Korean chili paste. Then, imagine that broccoli salad from your picnic crashing the party, so in addition to the chili-roasted florets you'll find sweet-tart dried cranberries and crunchy almonds strewn all over like confetti. Now think about taking this salad shindig to your own kitchen table. Hey, how do we score an invite to this party?

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Trim and thinly
slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced), separating whites from greens; mince whites.

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%tablespoon}, 3⁄4 of the @Korean chili flakes{1%teaspoon} (use less if you're not a fan of spicy food; reserve a pinch for the next step), a big pinch of @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @gochujang sauce{1%tablespoon}, @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, scallion whites, and a pinch of remaining chili flakes.

Slowly whisk in 3 TBSP oil (6 TBSP for 4 servings) until combined. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Add a pinch of sugar if you like a sweeter dressing!

Pat @chicken breast strips{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; cut into bite-size pieces if necessary. Season with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken in a single layer and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Add @ponzu sauce{6%milliliters} and 2 TBSP dressing (4 TBSP for 4 servings); stir to coat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

In a #large bowl{}, toss @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce}, broccoli, scallion greens, and half the chicken with as much remaining dressing as you like. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide salad between bowls. Top with remaining chicken, @dried cranberries{1%ounce}, and @sliced almonds{1/2%ounce}. Serve.